"Dallanave E., Tauxe L., Muttoni G., Rio D.","Silicate weathering machine at work: Rock magnetic data from the late Paleocene-early Eocene Cicogna section, Italy",2010,"Geochemistry, Geophysics, Geosystems","11","7", Q07008,"","",,,10.1029/2010GC003142,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-80052228913&partnerID=40&md5=b0566a982914ecb189d8e8b0bc0645d0","Department of Geosciences, University of Padova, Via Giotto 1, I-35137 Padua, Italy; Alpine Laboratory of Paleomagnetism, Via Madonna dei Boschi 76, I-12016 Peveragno, Italy; Scripps Institution of Oceanography, UCSD, 9500 Gilman Drive, San Diego, CA 92093-0220, United States; Department of Earth Sciences, University of Milan, Via Mangiagalli, 34, I-20133 Milan, Italy","Dallanave, E., Department of Geosciences, University of Padova, Via Giotto 1, I-35137 Padua, Italy, Alpine Laboratory of Paleomagnetism, Via Madonna dei Boschi 76, I-12016 Peveragno, Italy; Tauxe, L., Scripps Institution of Oceanography, UCSD, 9500 Gilman Drive, San Diego, CA 92093-0220, United States; Muttoni, G., Alpine Laboratory of Paleomagnetism, Via Madonna dei Boschi 76, I-12016 Peveragno, Italy, Department of Earth Sciences, University of Milan, Via Mangiagalli, 34, I-20133 Milan, Italy; Rio, D., Department of Geosciences, University of Padova, Via Giotto 1, I-35137 Padua, Italy","We describe a scenario of climate forcing on sedimentation recorded in the late Paleocene-early Eocene Cicogna marine section from the Belluno Basin (NE Italy). Previously published magneto-biostratigraphic data revealed that the ∼81 m Cicogna section extends from Chron C25r to Chron C23r spanning the NP7/NP8-NP12 nannofossil zones (∼52.2-56.6 Ma). Using previously published rock magnetic data, augmented by data from this study, we describe and thoroughly discuss a pronounced increase of hematite (relative to maghemite or magnetite) between ∼54.9 and 54.6 Ma immediately above the Paleocene-Eocene boundary, followed by a second, long-term increasing trend from ∼54 Ma up to ∼52.2 Ma in the early Eocene. This hematite is essentially of detrital origin, insofar as it is associated with a strong shallow bias of paleomagnetic inclinations, and is interpreted to have formed on land by the weathering of Fe-bearing silicates and other primary minerals. We speculate that the warm and humid climate typical of the Paleocene-Eocene thermal maximum (PETM, ∼54.9 Ma) as well as of the warming trend leading to the early Eocene climatic optimum (EECO; ∼52-50 Ma) enhanced continental weathering of silicate rocks with the consequent production, transport, and sedimentation of detrital hematite grains. This hypothesis is confirmed by a statistical correlation between the rock magnetic properties and global climate as revealed by a standard benthic oxygen isotope record from the literature. Our temporal coupling between oxidation state of sedimentary magnetic phases and global climate is therefore consistent with the existence in the Paleocene-Eocene of the silicate weathering negative feedback mechanism for the long-term stabilization of the Earth's surface temperature. Copyright 2010 by the American Geophysical Union.","Eocene; Global warming; Hematite; Maghemite; Paleocene; Silicate weathering","Earth (planet); Geomagnetism; Global warming; Hematite; Iron ores; Isotopes; Lithology; Magnetic properties; Magnetic storage; Rocks; Silicate minerals; Soil mechanics; State feedback; Benthic oxygen isotope; Climate forcings; Earth's surface; Eocene; Global climates; Humid climates; Maghemites; Magnetic data; Magnetic phasis; Negative feedback mechanism; Oxidation state; Paleocene; Paleocene-eocene thermal maximums; Rock magnetic properties; Silicate rocks; Silicate weathering; Statistical correlation; Temporal coupling; Weathering; biostratigraphy; chemical weathering; global warming; hematite; Hypsithermal; maghemite; magnetic property; magnetostratigraphy; Paleocene-Eocene boundary; paleomagnetism; rock property; silicate; surface tempera